{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/blepharitis/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"9a08c813-358a-52ed-8317-6734ad0caa2c","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 235dde9e-38b2-482a-886d-68d9b014d050 --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 235dde9e-38b2-482a-886d-68d9b014d050 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 081110dd-053e-4c4e-92b1-d3054f80a3a1 --><!-- begin field 8c1fa175-0783-40a0-92bd-5f870ffcd277 --><ul><li><strong>Blepharitis is a common condition:</strong><ul><li>It is estimated that about 5% of ophthalmological presentations in primary care are due to blepharitis.</li><li>A US based survey of ophthalmologists and optometrists found that blepharitis was seen in 37% of ophthalmology cases and 47% of optometrist cases.</li></ul></li><li>Blepharitis usually develops in middle-age but may also occur in childhood.<ul><li>The mean age of people with all types of blepharitis is 50 years.</li><li>Compared to other forms of blepharitis, staphylococcal blepharitis is more common at a slightly younger age (mean 42 years) and affects predominantly females (80%).</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/blepharitis/references/\">American Academy of Ophthalmology, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/blepharitis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>]</p><!-- end field 8c1fa175-0783-40a0-92bd-5f870ffcd277 --><!-- end item 081110dd-053e-4c4e-92b1-d3054f80a3a1 -->","topic":{"id":"210e4b01-890a-5a0a-a3cf-efcece1eb08e","topicId":"1bba37b4-ec1b-49d5-acc1-6fc1671711cf","topicName":"Blepharitis","slug":"blepharitis","lastRevised":"Last revised in AprilÂ 2019","chapters":[{"id":"b93c0a0c-4692-53c9-843f-49ee05545451","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"9c38019b-31fa-5b39-9bb8-b27769998a9b","